<br>
Those that are left at SOE are largely pragmatists - and incredibly skilled at making compromises to keep their current, dwindling player base happy. Similarly, they realize that the design team at Blizzard is dedicated to getting MMORPGs into the mainstream by eliminating timesinks, streamlining competition and creating relative bases of power, rather than absolute comparisons. The implications for this design choice are considerable and can have wide-reaching effects across the industry.<br>
<br>
In the end, though, one constant holds true. Subscription-based games rely upon people to continue playing for extended periods of time in order to generate income. Those hoping for a quick ending or instant gratification, regardless what game they play, will find themselves quickly disappointed. Like DikuMUD variants, EverQuest capitalizes on this successful mantra. Keep people addicted, and make it harder to break that addiction by placing never-ending goals. It remains to be seen how Star Wars Galaxies, or any other SOE game, will differ from that model, given just how successful EverQuest has been.<br>
<br>
