55th Evoker of E'ci <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=marcalus>Marcalus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#ffffff>(4/21/03 5:58:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=26165.topic&index=40>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Home cities</span><hr size=1> Warning...opinions ahead... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Here's the thing...<br>
<br>
Every single game that has tried to do &quot;EQ without the sucky parts&quot; has seemed flat by comparison.<br>
<br>
Let's talk DAoC, since that's where I spent a fair amount of time. (I was a guild leader on Gawaine for a while and a member of a pretty good alliance)<br>
<br>
You want an end-game that's not just fighting computer AI? Fine, we'll give you Realm versus Realm. However, the graphic engine couldn't handle the masses of people. Also, zerging each other was pretty much the most effective tactic. Level meant absolutely everything because of level-based modifiers (although these were taken out after I left, so perhaps it's better) Finally, &quot;losing&quot; at RvR was pretty much meaningless. Dying didn't cost you XP or gold...only time, and that's if you weren't able to be rezzed on the battlefield. Losing a keep or relic ultimately didn't really impact you...one dungeon in the game was &quot;shared&quot; and could only be entered by the &quot;winning&quot; team and that came later in the game. Not sure about the loot in there versus the loot elsewhere.<br>
<br>
Tradeskills. Let's talk tradeskills. Mythic listened to folk who didn't like having to collect components or travel to do tradeskills. Instead, doing tradeskills in Camelot pretty much consisted of standing in one spot 95% of your time. (you had to be near a forge or other appropriate location) When you ran out of raw materials, you scooted 20 feet over to the NPC and bought more and scooted back. When combining, a timer bar would pop up --- as the recipes got harder, this bar took longer to move. That was it, for well over a year. Has that gotten any more exciting or challenging? There was talk of adding in drops from critters for better recipes or of having ingredients in RvR only zones, but I don't think those ever flew.<br>
<br>
Boring.<br>
<br>
You're a caster? You automatically got all your spells every level. No research, no dropped spells, not a penny spent to buy them. I always found that kinda sad.<br>
<br>
Boredom is the game killer...and making things too easy and convienient makes it dull. Some of the very things that the casual player whines about (and I am one) are the things that give EQ depth. Yes, yes, yes...some of the tedious aspects can be dispensed with. Boat travel is cute the first few times, but the Kunark boat was downright painful. Melee having to beg for binds sucked...the soulbinders went in shortly after my cleric got Bind Affinity and I grumbled about not being able to charge...but got over it quickly as my ranger benefitted. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
EQ also has tons of fluff...like the booze code, fishing and other things that other games may throw out as &quot;extra, we don't need&quot; but that ultimately make the world a richer place. In my flirtation with Anarchy Online, for instance, I spent some time trying to get a pair of sunglasses. Did they actually do anything? No, but my character looked really cool with them. Does my wizard nuke better because he has a Fisherman's Companion? No...but people love it when I start passing the ale around!<br>
<br>
Again, my opinions....I find the difficulty and somewhat brutal nature of EQ one of it's charms. I know that I've earned my stuff and my levels and I've done some really cool quests in game.<br>
<br>
I am one of those younger folk, level wise, that Whizbang hints towards...my wizard is 38 and he's my highest character ever. You may read that last sentence and outright dismiss all my opionions, as I'm &quot;still a n00b&quot;. But I've also seen this stuff from the other side, having run one of the most popular NWN persistent worlds (<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nordock.net">www.nordock.net</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->). When your content is shallow, the userbase gets bored and either starts to eat itself (PvP or other forms of abusive behavior) or moves on. I think EQ is still the deepest game in the genre and will hold my attention for quite some time to come.<br>
<br>
And to answer the original question, I still pop into Ak'Anon on a semi-regular basis. I know the vendors and eveything is at the proper height. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.bellatlantic.net/~vze2n6q6/morlar.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
